<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-27T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="390" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d390">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.516/599: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-27T14:00:00-04:00">May 27,
                                    1939—2 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>189. Your 367, May 9, 6 p.m. Inasmuch as customs revenues in north China
                            have been since March 1938 payable in so-called Federal Reserve Bank
                            notes and those notes have usually been at a discount in relation to
                            Chinese national currency, the Department desires that you endeavor to
                            verify the information given you by the Customs to the effect that the
                            Customs revenues held in Tientsin and other north China ports are in the
                            form of deposits payable in Chinese national currency.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>